First, the basic idea: Use a custom map (with a custom reduction). 
Next, the trick is to sort the array before applying the custom reduction. That means sorting the array in reverse order, so "holes" won't appear between holes.
The trick is to use the first element from the array as the "hole" (i.e., you start with an index of 1 instead of a 2). To figure out how many items are in the array, you can just use the length of the array, to ensure that an "intermediate element is not included in the output of the reduction."
To make this work, you also have to make sure "holes" do not split the array in smaller arrays. I did some work to figure this out; it takes quite a bit of work, but it does work.
